Losing Face: Racial Bias in Biometric Recognition Technology

"I guess the computer got it wrong"

Robert Williams was given no explanation when he was taken into custody this past January. At the time, the Detroit police department was actively investigating a robbery at a trendy Shinola retail store, where five watches were stolen. Williams was misidentified as the shoplifter by Michigan state police’s facial recognition software and detained for 30 hours straight. Charges were dropped once a detective realized that “the computer got it wrong,” making this incident the first wrongful arrest in the U.S. due to a facial recognition mismatch.
